Title: Zurich
Description:
With around 434,335 inhabitants Zürich is the largest city of Switzerland. Nearby is Zürich Kloten (LSZH), the largest commercial airport of Switzerland.

Zürich is among the world's largest financial centres despite having a relatively small population.

In November 2008 the people of Zürich voted in a public referendum to write into law the quantifiable and fixed deadline of one tonne of CO2 per person per annum by 2050.

Title: Geneva Approach
Description: Geneva Airport, still unofficially known as Cointrin Airport, is next to Geneva, the second most populous city of Switzerland. The airport has a single concrete runway (04/22), which is the longest in Switzerland with a length of 3,900 m (12,795 ft) and one of the longest in Europe, making it open to use by aircraft of all existing sizes.\n\nMake an approach, coming from the west, onto runway 04.

Title: Montreux
Description: Montreux is a Swiss municipality and town on the shoreline of Lake Geneva at the foot of the Alps.\n\nIt is also well-known for its yearly Montreux Jazz Festival. The famous song Smoke on the Water by Deep Purple (1972) had its origins here, as it chronicles the 1971 fire at Montreux Casino.

Title: Valais
Description: The Rhône Valley is a central Alpine valley, i.e. it lies well within the Alps and is shut off from both northern and southern plains. Valais is separated from the Swiss Plateau to the north by the Bernese Alps and from the Po plains to the south by the Valais Alps, respectively north and south of the Rhône.\n\nThe Valais (French) or Wallis (German) is the third largest canton of Switzerland by area.

Title: Matterhorn
Description: The Matterhorn is a mountain of the Alps, straddling the main watershed and border between Switzerland and Italy. It is a large, near-symmetric pyramidal peak in the extended Monte Rosa area of the Pennine Alps, whose summit is 4,478 metres (14,692 ft) high, making it one of the highest summits in the Alps and Europe.

Title: Samedan Approach
Description: Samedan Airport (LSZS), also known as Engadin Airport, is a regional airport in Samedan in the Engadin valley of Switzerland, 5 km from St. Moritz. At an elevation of 1,707 metres (5,600 ft), it is the second highest airliner airport in Europe (with Courchevel being the highest).\n\nIt is also considered one of the most challenging airports in the world because of its difficult topography and winds, and because of the thinness of the air at its altitude.

Title: Verzasca Dam
Description: The Contra Dam, commonly known as the Verzasca Dam and the Locarno Dam, is an arch dam on the Verzasca River in the Val Verzasca of Ticino, Switzerland.\n\nIt also served as the filming location for the opening scene of the James Bond movie Goldeneye (1995). Fly with a PC-6 Porter, for maximum authenticity.

Title: The Great Aletsch Glacier
Description: The Aletsch Glacier is the largest glacier in the Alps. It has a length of about 23 km, located in the eastern Bernese Alps in the Swiss canton of Valais. The Aletsch Glacier is composed of four smaller glaciers converging at Konkordiaplatz.\n\nThe whole area, including other glaciers is part of the Jungfrau-Aletsch Protected Area, which was declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2001.

Title: Lauterbrunnen Valley
Description: The Lauterbrunnen Valley is located at the foot of the Bernese Alps. It is notably overlooked by the Eiger, Mönch and Jungfrau and many other high peaks.\n\nJ. R. R. Tolkien hiked from Interlaken to the Lauterbrunnen Valley while on a trip to the Continent in 1911. The landscape of the valley later provided the concept and pictorial model for his sketches and watercolours of the fictitious valley of Rivendell, the dwelling place of Elrond Half-elven and his people.

Title: Thun
Description: Thun is a town and a municipality in the administrative district of Thun in the canton of Bern in Switzerland. It is located where the Aare flows out of Lake Thun (Thunersee), 30 kilometres (19 miles) southeast of Bern.

Title: Bern
Description: Bern is the de facto capital of Switzerland, referred to as the federal city. With a population of about 144,000 (as of 2020), Bern is the fourth-most populous city in Switzerland.

Title: Buochs
Description: The Buochs Airport (LSZC) is a regional airport in the town of Buochs in the Canton of Nidwalden in Switzerland. It has a concrete runway with a length of 2000 meters and a width of 40 meters, several taxiways and hangars.\n\nThe nearby Pilatus Aircraft site was used as filming location for the James Bond movie Goldfinger (1964).

Title: Dead Vlei
Description: Dead Vlei is a white clay pan located near the more famous salt pan of Sossusvlei, inside the Namib-Naukluft Park in Namibia. Dead Vlei has been claimed to be surrounded by the highest sand dunes in the world, the highest reaching 300–400 meters, named Big Daddy or Crazy Dune.\n\nFilms partly shot there include The Cell (2000), The Fall (2006), and Ghajini (2008).

Title: Mount Ngauruhoe
Description: Mount Ngāuruhoe is a fairly active volcanic cone in New Zealand that has first erupted about 2,500 years ago.\n\nMount Ngāuruhoe was used as a stand-in for the fictional Mount Doom in Peter Jackson's The Lord of the Rings film trilogy, achieving worldwide exposure.

Title: Santons Dumont Approach
Description:
Santos Dumont Airport (SBRJ) is the second major airport serving Rio de Janeiro. It is named after the Brazilian aviation pioneer Alberto Santos Dumont (1873–1932).

Aim for the Sugar Loaf and then take a sharp left turn. The approach takes you from the northwest over central Rio, where you have to negotiate the mountainous terrain not just around Sugar Loaf, but also around the central west of Rio.

After this spectacular left turn take the aircraft down onto runway 02R. ILS would guide you straight through the Sugar Loaf, so this is VFR only.

Title: St. Vincent and the Grenadines
Description: Saint Vincent and the Grenadines is an island country in the Caribbean. Kingstown is the capital and main port.\n\nIt is thought that Christopher Columbus sighted the island in 1498, giving it the name St Vincent.

Title: Bora Bora
Description: Bora Bora is an island group in the Leeward Islands. In the center of the island are the remnants of an extinct volcano, rising to two peaks, Mount Pahia and Mount Otemanu.

Title: Richat Structure
Description: The Richat Structure, also called Guelb er Richât, is a prominent circular geological feature in the Sahara's Adrar Plateau, near Ouadane, west–central Mauritania, Northwest Africa. It is an eroded geological dome, 40 kilometres (25 mi) in diameter, exposing sedimentary rock in layers which appear as concentric rings.

Title: Grand Canyon
Description: The Grand Canyon is a steep-sided canyon carved by the Colorado River in Arizona, United States. The Grand Canyon is 277 miles (446 km) long, up to 18 miles (29 km) wide and attains a depth of over a mile (6,093 feet or 1,857 meters).

Title: Monument Valley
Description: Monument Valley (Navajo: Tsé Biiʼ Ndzisgaii, meaning valley of the rocks) is a region of the Colorado Plateau characterized by a cluster of sandstone buttes, the largest reaching 1,000 ft (300 m) above the valley floor. It is located on the Utah-Arizona state line, near the Four Corners area. The valley is a sacred area that lies within the territory of the Navajo Nation Reservation, the Native American people of the area.\n\nDirector John Ford used the location for a number of his Westerns; critic Keith Phipps wrote that ‹‹its five square miles [13 square kilometers] have defined what decades of moviegoers think of when they imagine the American West››.

Title: Cape Eleuthera, Bahamas
Description: Eleuthera refers both to a single island in the archipelagic state of The Commonwealth of the Bahamas and to its associated group of smaller islands. Eleuthera forms a part of the Great Bahama Bank. The island of Eleuthera incorporates the smaller Harbour Island. ‹‹Eleuthera›› derives from the feminine form of the Greek adjective ἐλεύθερος (eleútheros), meaning ‹‹free››.

Title: Hong Kong
Description: Hong Kong is one of the most densely populated places in the world. Hong Kong is also a major global financial centre and one of the most developed cities in the world.\n\nThe city has the largest number of skyscrapers of any city in the world, and its residents have some of the highest life expectancies in the world. The dense space has led to a highly developed transportation network with public transport rates exceeding 90%.

Title: Hyderabad
Description: Hyderabad is the capital and largest city of the Indian state of Telangana and the de jure capital of Andhra Pradesh. It occupies 650 km2 (250 sq mi) on the Deccan Plateau along the banks of the Musi River, in the northern part of Southern India. With an average altitude of 542 m (1,778 ft), much of Hyderabad is situated on hilly terrain around artificial lakes, including the Hussain Sagar lake, predating the city's founding, in the north of the city centre.\n\nAccording to the 2011 Census of India, Hyderabad is the fourth-most populous city in India with a population of 6.9 million residents within the city limits, and has a population of 9.7 million residents in the metropolitan region, making it the sixth-most populous metropolitan area in India.

Title: Paris
Description: Paris is the capital and most populous city of France, with an estimated population of 2,165,423 residents in 2019 in an area of more than 105 km² (41 sq mi). Since the 17th century, Paris has been one of the world's major centres of finance, diplomacy, commerce, fashion, gastronomy, science, and arts, and has sometimes been referred to as the capital of the world.\n\nParis is a major railway, highway, and air-transport hub served by two international airports: Paris–Charles de Gaulle (the second-busiest airport in Europe) and Paris–Orly.

Title: Heisenberg
Description: 34°59'20.0'' N 106°36'52.0'' W - the end of the rainbow? Or maybe not quite. In any case, this is the location of the production studio of some world-famous TV series.

Title: Como Hidroport Airport
Description: Travelers and merchants alike have been attracted to Lake Como from time immemorial. The ancient Romans called it Larius, George Clooney calls it home. This glacier lake nestled in the folds of the Alps and lined by picturesque villages, majestic villas, and mountains covered with foliage ranging from palm trees to cypresses, is one of the most beautiful lakes in Europe. One could argue that neighboring Lake Garda and Lake Maggiore are equally stunning, but only the shores of Lake Como can boast of the world’s oldest seaplane operation, the Aero Club Como.\n\nThe Aero Club Como was founded in 1930. However, seaplane operations went on at the same location as early as 1913, most notably the Gran Premio dei Laghi—a rally in which French pilot Roland Garros, who would become a World War I hero, competed flying a Morane-Saulnier. The current hangar is located at the space that served as the base of operations for this event.

Title: University Hospital Zurich
Description: This helipad on the rooftop of the University Hospital of Zurich (USZ) provides a landing spot for the Swiss air rescue (Rega) helicopters.\n\nWith its three ambulance jets and its 14 helicopter bases distributed all over the country, Rega is an integral part of primary medical care in Switzerland. In 2021, Rega came to the aid of more than 12,000 patients and organised about 18,000 missions.

Title: Doha
Description:
Doha is the capital city and main financial hub of Qatar. Located on the Persian Gulf coast in the east of the country, north of Al Wakrah and south of Al Khor, it is home to most of the country's population. It is also Qatar's fastest growing city, with over 80% of the nation's population living in Doha or its surrounding suburbs.

The city also hosted the 2012 UNFCCC Climate Negotiations and the 2022 FIFA World Cup.

The city is served by Hamad International Airport (ICAO: OTHH), the home of Qatar’s flag carrier airline, Qatar Airways.

Title: One more time!
Description:
The largest wooden airplane ever built.

The Spruce Goose was first conceived during World War II, when German submarines were sinking hundreds of Allied ships, and there was a growing need to move troops and materials across the Atlantic Ocean. Henry Kaiser conceived the idea of a massive flying transport and turned to Howard Hughes to design and build it. Hughes took on the task, made even more challenging by the government’s restrictions on materials critical to the war effort, such as steel and aluminum.

Six times larger than any aircraft of its time, the Spruce Goose, also known as the Hughes Flying Boat, is made entirely of wood and flew just one time on November 2, 1947, in Long Beach, California.

Title: Where it all began…
Description: Merrill C. Meigs Field Airport was a single-runway airport in Chicago that was in operation from December 1948 until March 2003 on Northerly Island, an artificial peninsula on Lake Michigan. Meigs Field airport was opened on December 10, 1948, and, by 1955, had become the busiest single-strip airport in the United States.\n\nMeigs was the default airport for the Microsoft Flight Simulator series until Microsoft Flight Simulator 2004, though the airport remains operational in Flight Simulator 2004. In Flight Simulator X, it was completely removed from the scenery, up until the Steam Edition of the game added it as downloadable content in 2015. The scenery was also recreated with the 40th Anniversary Update for MSFS 2020.

Title: Mauna Loa
Description: Hawaii’s Mauna Loa volcano is the largest active in the world. The 5,000 square kilometre volcano is situated inside Hawaii Volcanoes National Park. It is one of five volcanoes that form the Island of Hawaii in the U.S. state of Hawaii in the Pacific Ocean.\n\nIt erupted on November 27 2022, the first time after nearly 40 years since its last eruption in 1984.

Title: McMurdo Station
Description:
McMurdo Station is a United States Antarctic research station on the south tip of Ross Island, which is in the New Zealand-claimed Ross Dependency on the shore of McMurdo Sound in Antarctica. It is operated by the United States through the United States Antarctic Program (USAP), a branch of the National Science Foundation.

The station is the largest community in Antarctica, capable of supporting up to 1,258 residents,[2] and serves as one of three year-round United States Antarctic science facilities. All personnel and cargo going to or coming from Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station first pass through McMurdo. By road, McMurdo is 3 kilometres (1.9 mi) from New Zealand's smaller Scott Base.

Take-off point is a nearby ice runway in the west of the station - so don't forget to bring your skis with you.

Title: Diavik Diamond Mine
Description: The Diavik Diamond Mine is a diamond mine in the North Slave Region of the Northwest Territories, Canada, about 300 km northeast of Yellowknife.

Title: Cerro Roma
Description: Cerro Roma is a mountain in the Andes mountain range, located on the border between Argentina and Chile, in the Patagonia region.

Title: Mazār-i-Sharīf
Description: Mazār-e Sharīf, or Mazar, is the 4th largest city of Afghanistan and capital of the Balkh province. This region of northern Afghanistan is a tourist and pilgrimage destination due to its famous shrines and archeological sites.\n\n These spectacular mountains lie southeast stretching for hundreds of kilometers and can be reached easily from the Mazar Airport (OAMS).

Title: Northumberlandia
Description: Jogging slopes draw the silhouette of a woman in a field.

Title: Capri
Description: The picturesque small island of Capri lies at the far south of the Gulf of Naples. It's a long flight from Naples in a prop plane but the island is nicely rendered with steep rocky cliffs and the two scenic island towns of Capri and Anacapri.  It's a good 20-30 minutes from Naples across the Gulf at 80 knots.

Title: Shoemaker Crater
Description: Shoemaker (formerly known as Teague Ring) is an impact structure, the deeply eroded remnant of a former impact crater, situated in arid central Western Australia, about 100 km (62 mi) north-northeast of Wiluna. It is named in honour of planetary geologist Eugene Shoemaker.

Title: Zhangye National Geopark
Description: The Zhangye Natural Geopark, formerly known as Zhangye Danxia Geopark, is a stunning collection of bizarre and colorful rock formations found in the foothills of the Quilian Mountains in China’s Gansu Province.

Title: Grand Staircase–Escalante National Monument
Description: Grand Staircase–Escalante National Monument is a large area of varied desert topography in the state of Utah. It is some of the most remote land anywhere in the continental United States, in fact, it was the last region in the contiguous 48 American states to be mapped. There are a variety of canyons reaching all the way south to the Lake Powell recreation area in southern Utah.

Title: Krontosky
Description: Kronotsky is a major stratovolcano on the Kamchatka Peninsula, Russia. It is located in Kronotsky Nature Reserve to the east of Lake Kronotskoye ( the largest lake in Kamchatka. It has a particularly symmetrical conical shape, comparable to Mount Fuji in Japan and to Mayon Volcano in the Philippines. Kronotsky is considered to be one of the most scenic volcanoes in Kamchatka.

Title: Kenai Fjords National Park
Description: Kenai Fjords National Park is located in Alaska. Take off from Anchorage (PANC) and follow one of the mountain passes to Seward at the tip of Resurrection Bay. From there head south and west. There are several prominent Fjords and over 10 glaciers to explore within the borders of the park.

Title: Fogo Island, Cape Verde
Description: Largest of the volcanos in Cape Verde Islands.

Title: Namib Desert
Description:
The Namib desert (local meaning 'Vast place') stretches for more than 2000km along the Southwest coast of Africa. The massive dunes are the second largest in the world, after the Badain Jaran desert of China.

Fogs that originate offshore from the collision of the cold Benguela Current and warm air from the Hadley Cell create a fog belt that frequently envelops parts of the desert. Coastal regions can experience more than 180 days of thick fog a year. While this has proved a major hazard to ships—more than a thousand wrecks litter the Skeleton Coast—it is a vital source of moisture for desert life.

The Namib is almost completely uninhabited by humans except for several small settlements and indigenous pastoral groups.

Title: Wake Island
Description: Take off of Wake Island Airfield  (PWAK) and discover history.

Title: Saint-Malo
Description: Saint-Malo is a historic French port on the English Channel coast. A walled city with a long history of piracy; earning much wealth from local extortion and noteworthy, overseas adventures. In 1944, the Allies heavily bombarded the city, which was garrisoned by German troops. The city changed into a popular tourist center, with a ferry terminal serving the Channel Islands of Jersey and Guernsey, as well as the Southern English settlements of Portsmouth, Hampshire and Poole, Dorset.

Title: Arecibo Observatory
Description: Arecibo Telescope which unfortunately collapsed on December 1 2020.

Title: Momella Lakes
Description: This location can be seen at the start the Xbox gameplay trailer, and includes numerous fauna species. However, it is not marked on the world map. It could therefore be considered an easter egg. There is a small pier perfect for docking a small seaplane, and the area is surrounded by the beautiful Arusha National Park and nearby Mount Kilimanjaro.

Title: Lofoten Ilands
Description: Lofoten  is an archipelago and a traditional district in the county of Nordland, Norway. Lofoten has distinctive scenery with dramatic mountains and peaks, open sea and sheltered bays, beaches and untouched lands.

Title: Wolfe Creek Meteorite Crater
Description: Wolfe Creek Crater is a well-preserved meteorite impact crater in Western Australia.

Title: Mo'orea Island
Description: Mo'orea, also spelled Moorea, is a volcanic island in French Polynesia. It is one of the Windward Islands, a group that is part of the Society Islands, 17 kilometres (11 mi) northwest of Tahiti. The name comes from the Tahitian word Mo'ore'a, meaning "yellow lizard", An older name for the island is 'Aimeho, sometimes spelled 'Aimeo or 'Eimeo (among other spellings that were used by early visitors before Tahitian spelling was standardized). Early Western colonists and voyagers also referred to Mo'orea as York Island.

Title: Torres de Paine
Description: The beautiful Serrano river flows throught the Torres del Paine National Park.\n\nIt is a national park encompassing mountains, glaciers, lakes, and rivers in southern Chilean Patagonia. The Cordillera del Paine is the centerpiece of the park. It lies in a transition area between the Magellanic subpolar forests and the Patagonian Steppes.  Paine means "blue" in the native Tehuelche (Aonikenk) language and is pronounced PIE-nay, while Torres means "towers".

Title: Out Skerries
Description: The Out Skerries are an archipelago of islets, some inhabited, in Shetland, Scotland, and are the easternmost group of Shetland's islands. Locally, they are usually called Da Skerries or just Skerries.

Title: Gosses Bluff Crater
Description: Gosses Bluff is thought to be the eroded remnant of an impact crater. Known as Tnorala to the Western Arrente people of the surrounding region, it is located in the southern Northern Territory.

Title: Haughton Impact Crater
Description: Haughton impact crater is located on Devon Island, Nunavut in far Northern Canada. It is about 23 km in diameter and formed about 39 million years ago during the late Eocene.

Title: Lake Kuttara
Description: Lake Kuttara is a nearly circular caldera lake in Shiraoi, Hokkaidō, Japan. It is part of Shikotsu-Tōya National Park. The lake is recognized as having the best water quality in all of Japan.

Title: Popocatépetl Volcano
Description: Popocatépetl is an active stratovolcano located in the states of Puebla, Morelos, and Mexico in central Mexico.

Title: Zanzibar
Description: Unguja, also known as Zanzibar Island, is the main island in the Tanzanian archipelago of Zanzibar. Stone Town, part of Zanzibar City, is an old trade center, with mosques and winding lanes.\n\nYou can see amazing water mask along its beach.

Title: Lake Ichkeul
Description: Lake Ichkeul is a lake in northern Tunisia, located 20 kilometres (12 miles) to Bizerte, the northernmost city in Africa on the Mediterranean Sea. The lake and wetlands of Ichkeul National Park are an important stopping-over point for hundreds of thousands of migrating birds each year. Among the lake's visitors are ducks, geese, storks, and pink flamingoes. Dam construction on the lake's feeder rivers has produced major changes to the ecological balance of the lake and wetlands.

Title: Yendegaia National Park
Description: Yendegaia National Park is located in Tierra del Fuego in the Magallanes y la Antártica Chilena Region of Chile and contains 150,612 ha (372,170 acres) of mountainous terrain and Valdivian temperate rain forest. It borders the Alberto de Agostini National Park and Tierra del Fuego National Park.

Title: Cape Eleuthera
Description: Eleuthera refers both to a single island in the archipelagic state of The Commonwealth of the Bahamas and to its associated group of smaller islands. Eleuthera forms a part of the Great Bahama Bank. The island of Eleuthera incorporates the smaller Harbour Island. "Eleuthera" derives from the feminine form of the Greek adjective ἐλεύθερος (eleútheros), meaning "free".

Title: Behringer Meteor Crater
Description: Behringer Meteor Crater is a meteorite impact crater about 37 mi (60 km) east of Flagstaff, Arizona.  The crater was created about 50,000 years ago during the Pleistocene epoch when a nickel-iron meteorite about 160 ft (50 m) across collided with Earth.

Title: Volcán Lanín
Description: Lanín is an ice-clad, cone-shaped stratovolcano on the border of Argentina and Chile. It forms part of two national parks: Lanín in Argentina and Villarrica in Chile. It is a symbol of the Argentine province of Neuquén, being part of its flag and its anthem. Although the date of its last eruption is not known, it is estimated to have occurred within the last 10,000 years.

Title: Lagoa das Sete Cidades
Description: It's a twin lake on a volcano crater, located at the island of São Miguel, archipelago of Azores, Portugal. \n\nIts name literally means "Lagoon of the Seven Cities".

Title: Vinicunca (Rainbow mountain)
Description: The Vinicunca mountain is colored by several rock materials.

Title: Black Rocks of Pungo Andongo
Description: The Black Rocks of Pungo Andongo are dramatic rock formations springing up from the flat Savanna of southern Angola. These impressive desert monoliths were associated with tribal legend for the indigenous peoples of the region. While not appearing black in the Sim, these rock formations are still impressive, especially given the remarkable contrast to the flat desert surroundings.

Title: The Great Blue Hole
Description: The Great Blue Hole is a giant marine sinkhole off the coast of Belize. It lies near the center of Lighthouse Reef, a small atoll 70 km from the mainland and Belize City.

Title: Machu Picchu
Description: Iconic hilltop ruins of a large 15th-century Inca city featuring numerous structures & terraces.

Title: Juani Island
Description: Beautiful water masking surrounding Juani Island. Part of the Rufiji Mafia Kilwa Marine Reserve, located in the three districts of Rufiji, Mafia and Kilwa, within the Coast and Lindi regions of southeast Tanzania.\n\nThe area is listed as a world heritage site.

Title: Dahlak Marine National Park
Description: Flamingo spotting.

Title: Eye of the Sahara
Description: Possible location of the Lost City of Atlantis according to Plato.

Title: Mount Cook National Park
Description: The Misty Mountains... Mr Frodo.

Title: Sani Pass
Description: Sani Pass is a mountain pass located in the West of KwaZulu-Natal, South Africa on the road between Underberg, KwaZulu-Natal and Mokhotlong, Lesotho.

Title: Mont Blanc
Description: Mont Blanc (meaning "white mountain") is the highest mountain in the Alps and Western Europe, rising 4,807.81 m (15,774 ft) above sea level. It is the second-most prominent mountain in Europe, after Mount Elbrus, and it is the eleventh most prominent mountain summit in the world.

Title: Wadi Rum
Description: Wadi Rum (also Wādī al-Ramm), known also as the Valley of the Moon, is a valley cut into the sandstone and granite rock in southern Jordan 60 km (37 mi) to the east of Aqaba; it is the largest wadi in Jordan.

Title: Al Farafra Desert
Description: This desert includes some remarkable sand waves and geological formations.

Title: Mount Iwaki
Description: Mount Iwaki is a stratovolcano located in western Aomori Prefecture, Tohoku, Japan. It is also referred to as Tsugaru Fuji and less frequently, Okufuji due to its similar shape to Mount Fuji. With a summit elevation of 1,625 meters and a prominence of 1,322 meters it is the highest mountain in Aomori Prefecture.

Title: Island of Costaérès
Description: The Château de Costaérès is located on the island of Costaérès in the territory of the French commune of Trégastel, in Côtes-d'Armor, Brittany.

Title: Wakhan Corridor,
Description: The Wakhan Corridor is a narrow strip of territory in Afghanistan, extending to China and separating Tajikistan from Pakistan and Kashmir.\n\nWith a difference of 3.5 hours, the border Afghanistan-China has the sharpest official change of clocks of any international frontier (UTC+4:30 in Afghanistan to UTC+8, in China).

Title: McMurdo Dry Valleys
Description: The McMurdo Dry Valleys are a row of largely snow-free valleys in Antarctica, located within Victoria Land west of McMurdo Sound. The Dry Valleys experience extremely low humidity and surrounding mountains prevent the flow of ice from nearby glaciers.

Title: Burj Al Arab Helipad
Description: Helipad

Title: Brukkaros Crater
Description: Brukkaros Mountain (Khoekhoe: Geitsi Gubib) is a collapsed caldera in ǁKaras Region, Namibia. Measuring 1,590 metres at its peak on the eastern edge of the crater, Brukkaros is located about 15 kilometres northeast of the primarily Nama town of Berseba and 100 kilometres north-northwest of Keetmanshoop.[1] It is over 650 metres taller than the surrounding area, but the crater floor is 350 m below the rim.

Title: Alaniya National Park
Description: The Alaniya National Park sits on the border of Russia and Georgia in the Caucasus Mountain range.

MigrationId: This is a very mountainous area with lots of nice glaciers to check out.
Title: PA
Description: RU

Title: Mafia Island
Description: Mafia Island is an island and district of Pwani Region, Tanzania. The island is the third largest in Tanzanian ocean territory, but is not administratively included within the semi-autonomous region of Zanzibar, which has been politically separate since 1890. Mafia Island forms the major part of Mafia District, one of the six administrative districts in the Pwani coastal region.

Title: Salinas Grandes
Description: The spectacular Salinas Grandes in the north western part of Argentina is a salt plain that covers an area of 212 km2 and sits at an altitude of 3500 meters above sea level.\n\nIt’s the remnant of a lake that dried up in the Holocene and the area is now covered with a 0.5m thick salt crust.

Title: Providencia Island
Description: Isla de Providencia, historically Old Providence, and generally known as Providencia, is a mountainous Caribbean island that is part of the Colombian department of Archipelago of San Andrés, Providencia and Santa Catalina and the municipality of Providencia and Santa Catalina Islands, lying midway between Costa Rica and Jamaica.

Title: Dasht-e Lut
Description: The Lut Desert, widely referred to as Dasht-e Lut ("Emptiness Plain"), is a large salt desert located in the provinces of Kerman and Sistan and Baluchestan, Iran. It is the world's 33rd-largest desert, and was included on UNESCO's World Heritage List on July 17, 2016. The name is derived from 'Lut' which means bare and empty in Persian and 'dasht' which means plain in Persian. The surface of its sand has been measured at temperatures as high as 70.7 °C (159.3 °F), making it one of the world's driest and hottest places.

Title: Kolsaiskie
Description: Kolsay Lakes National Park is located on the north slope of the Tian Shan Mountains, southeast Kazakhstan. Often referred to as "Pearls of Tien Shan", the park's main feature are the Kolsay Lakes located between the Raiymbek District and Talgar District of Almaty Region.

Title: St. George, Grenada
Description: The beautiful country of Grenada is located in the Caribbean and Is surrounded by an abundance of coral reefs. \n\nTake off from the Capital, St. George (TGPY) and fly circle the Island for a birds eye view of the colourful homes and great scenery. If you’re looking for a slightly longer route to fly, set course for the Island of Carriacou to the North East for some fantastic reefs.

Title: Shanghai
Description: With almost 25 million inhabitants, Shanghai is the most populous city in China and the second most populous city proper in the world. The city was first inhabited over 6000 years ago and is today known as a global finance, research and technology centre. Shanghai also houses the worlds busiest container port.\n\nThe Lujiazui skyline is famous for its iconic buildings. Such as the Shanghai Tower, The Shanghai World Financial Centre, Jin Mao Tower and possible the most famous Oriental Pearl Tower.

Title: Minna Island
Description: This small Island sits in between the two Japanese islands of Miyakojima and Ishigaki Island. The Island is surrounded by beautiful reefs.

Title: Balochistan
Description:
This spot is exactly a few miles east from the highest mountain top "Loe sar Nekan", in the province of Baluchistan in the southwest of Pakistan.

Loe sar Nekan is located 30 km east-north-east of the city of Quetta in the Zarghun Ghar mountain massif. Loe sar Nekan peak has a height of 3575 m.

On the west side of the mountain range is  Quetta Int'l Airport (OPQT).

Title: Ishigaki Island
Description: This beautiful Japanese Island is located around 411km south-west of Okinawa Honto. Much of the Island is protected as part of the Iriomote-Ishigaki National Park. Ishigaki Island is surrounded by fringing coral reefs of several hundred meters to 1 km in width.

Title: Etosha Pan
Description:
Africa’s largest salt pan, The Etosha Pan, is a vast open expanse of brilliant green and white. It’s so big it’s said to be visible from space. It is 130km long and up to 50km wide.

A long time ago the pan was a lake but over time, the climate forced the rivers that once fed the lake to change course and flow into the Atlantic Ocean instead.

The airports Okaukuejo Airport (FYOO) and Operet Airport (FYOU) are in the vicinity.

Title: Rann of Kutch
Description: The Great Raann of Kutch (કચ્છનું મોટું રણ) is a huge white salt marsh. It is India’s largest and offers a otherworldly landscape. It’s about 7500 square kilometre making it, possibly, the largest salt desert in the world.\n\nThis is one of the hottest areas of India – with summer temperatures averaging and peaking at 49.5 °C. Winter temperatures reduce dramatically and can go below 0 °C.

Title: Icy Bay, Alaska
Description: Icy Bay is a relatively young body of water in the southeast of Alaska. It has formed in the last 100 years due to the rapid retreat of two glaciers.\n\nThe bay is also famous for the 2015 landslide and megatsunami, where 181,000,000 metric tons of rock was dislodged when the side of a mountain collapsed.

Title: Lake Coipasa
Description: Lake Coipasa is a saline lake with a depth of 3.5 metres. It is surrounded by the Coipasa salt flat (Salar de Coipasa), and the volcanic cone of Wila Pukarani.\n\nThe lake is a breeding ground for flamingos with thousands having settled on the shores of Lake Coipasa.

Title: Anjihai Grand Canyon
Description: The Anjihai Grand Canyon, also known as the Hongshan (Red Mountain) Grand Canyon, is found at the northern foot of the Tianshan Mountains in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.

Title: Lençóis Maranhense
Description: A national park located in northeastern Brazil. The coastline is composed of Rolling sand dunes, who’s valleys fill during the rainy season and becomes fresh water lagoons.

Title: Palmanova
Description: Palmanova is a town and comune in northeastern Italy. The town is an example of star fort of the late Renaissance, built up by the Venetian Republic in 1593.\n\nThe fortifications were included in UNESCO's World Heritage Site list as part of Venetian Works of Defence between 15th and 17th centuries: Stato da Terra – western Stato da Mar in 2017.
